The paper deals with the complexity of solving constraint satisfaction problems (CSPs) using semidefinite programming (SDP) relaxations, which is a topic in computational complexity theory (cs.CC). The paper also involves the study of the structure of CSPs and their support, which is related to discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and graph theory (cs.CG). The use of the Sherali-Adams LP hierarchy and the Lasserre SDP hierarchy suggests a connection to optimization and approximation algorithms (cs.DS). Finally, the paper involves the study of the inapproximability of Max-CSPs, which is related to game theory (cs.GT).
